==English==

{{rank|gold|letters|history|589|master|latter|fellow|hardly}}
===Etymology===
Old English ''[[mæġester]]''

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-master.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɑːstə(r)|-ɑːstə(r)]]

===Noun===
'''master'''  (''plural:'' '''[[masters]]''')
# someone who has [[control]] over something or someone
# owner of an [[animal]] or [[slave]]
# the [[captain]] of a [[merchant ship]]; a [[master mariner]]
# someone who [[employ]]s others
# an [[expert]] at something
# a [[tradesman]] who is qualified to [[teach]] [[apprentice]]s
# a skilled [[artist]]
#{{dated}} a [[courtesy title]] of a man; [[mister]]
#a courtesy title for a boy
# the [[original]] of a [[document]] or of a [[recording]]
#{{cattag|Filmology}} The [[primary]] [[wide shot]] of a [[scene]], into which the [[closeup]]s will be edited later.

====Synonyms====
*(''film''): [[establishing shot]], [[long shot]]

